WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.640
Hi there, I'm Cedric Scherer and I have the honor to teach the upcoming workshop Engaging

00:00:09.640 --> 00:00:13.360
and Beautiful Data Visualizations with ggplot2 at the Posit Conference, which is going to

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:17.480
happen this year in September in Chicago.

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:20.760
The course is for anyone who already knows the fundamental principles of this graphics

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:26.920
library, but doesn't want to only create simple and basic charts, but go beyond that and create

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:32.360
custom and detailed graphics that stand out and successfully tell a story by guiding and

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:33.360
engaging the viewer.

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:37.439
So here are three main reasons why I think you don't want to miss this workshop.

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:43.040
The first is that you will get insights and hands-on experience on how to design advanced

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:45.840
data visualizations with code only.

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:51.320
I will share helpful tricks, exciting extension packages and other useful utilities that I've

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:54.439
gathered over the years working with this powerful library.

00:00:54.439 --> 00:01:00.040
A range of examples of popular and less common chart types will showcase the potential of

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:06.080
ggplot2 to create any graphic you can think of, all reproducible, transparent and without

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:07.680
the need for any manual post-processing.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:14.720
Second, you will learn how to leverage the power of ggplot2 to ensure a corporate and

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:17.800
custom look and be more efficient.

00:01:17.800 --> 00:01:22.839
I'll cover how to modify any aspect of your graphic and also how to create your own corporate

00:01:22.839 --> 00:01:28.680
themes and color scales with sensible defaults and personal options if you want.

00:01:28.680 --> 00:01:33.480
This will hopefully help you, your team and potential collaborators to design graphics

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:38.279
with a consistent look in a more efficient way while providing all the flexibility that

00:01:38.279 --> 00:01:40.480
ggplot2 has to offer.

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:43.680
And last but not least, you'll also learn how to create charts that provide a clear

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:45.800
narrative and guide the viewers.

00:01:45.800 --> 00:01:51.480
I will show you how to use suitable colors, modify labels, add annotations and other highlights

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:56.879
to enrich your visualizations, empowering you to apply the general basic principles

00:01:56.879 --> 00:02:00.519
of graphical storytelling when working with ggplot2.

00:02:00.519 --> 00:02:04.480
So these are some of the highlights of the upcoming workshop on ggplot2 and if this sounds

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:09.479
interesting, then don't miss this opportunity and join us at the POSIT conference in Chicago.

